# Project Architecture

This project is a Vue.js SPA frontend talking to a FastAPI backend, which persists data in MongoDB.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  userBrowser["UserBrowser"] --> vueApp["VueApp (SPA)"]
  vueApp --> fastApi["FastAPIBackend"]
  fastApi --> mongoDb["MongoDB"]
```

# Folder Layout

## Frontend (`frontend/`)

- `frontend/src/main.ts`: App bootstrap and global plugins.
- `frontend/src/router/`: Route definitions and route guards only.
- `frontend/src/components/`: Reusable, presentational components.
- `frontend/src/features/<feature>/`: Feature-specific screens, components, and logic.
  - `components/`: Feature-only components.
  - `stores/`: Pinia/Vuex stores for this feature.
  - `api/`: Small API client modules wrapping HTTP calls for this feature.
- `frontend/src/shared/` or `frontend/src/common/`: Cross-cutting UI pieces, utilities, and types.

## Backend (`backend/`)

- `backend/app/main.py`: FastAPI app creation and global middleware.
- `backend/app/api/` or `backend/app/routers/`: Route modules grouped by feature or resource.
- `backend/app/services/`: Business/use-case logic, orchestrating repositories and external services.
- `backend/app/schemas/`: Pydantic models for requests/responses.
- `backend/app/repositories/` or `backend/app/db/`: MongoDB data-access code (queries, aggregations).
- `backend/app/core/`: Settings, security, and other core infrastructure concerns.

## Infra (`infra/`) (optional)

- Deployment manifests, Dockerfiles, and environment configuration.

# Boundaries & Responsibilities

- Vue components handle UI, local state, and calling typed HTTP APIs; they do not contain business or persistence logic.
- Frontend `api` modules own HTTP details (URLs, headers, error mapping) and expose typed functions to the rest of the app.
- FastAPI routers focus on request/response wiring and delegate logic to services.
- Services (or use-case modules) implement business rules and call MongoDB through a dedicated data-access layer.
- MongoDB access is centralized (e.g., repositories/DAOs), not called directly from routers or Vue code.

# Minimal Conventions

- Prefer feature folders within `frontend/` and `backend/` when a domain grows (e.g., `frontend/src/features/dashboard`, `backend/app/api/dashboard`).
- Name Vue components in `PascalCase` (`DashboardPanel.vue`) and FastAPI modules in `snake_case` (`dashboard_routes.py`).
- In both frontend and backend, name feature folders by domain (e.g., `auth`, `dashboard`, `reports`) rather than technology.
- Add new endpoints under the appropriate router module and expose them via a small API client module in `frontend/src/features/<feature>/api/`.
- Keep cross-cutting utilities in clearly named `shared` or `common` subfolders rather than mixing them into feature folders.

# Design Principles

- **DRY, but not over-DRY**:
  - Extract shared logic when it is used in at least two meaningful places and has a clear name (e.g., `useFetchDashboard` or `dashboard_repository`).
  - Do not create abstractions for one-off cases or for code that is still evolving; duplication is acceptable until patterns are stable.
  - Prefer simple, local duplication over complex indirection that makes features harder to read or change.

- **Open for extension, closed for modification**:
  - Design routers, services, and components so that adding a new feature usually means adding new modules or functions, not editing many existing ones.
  - Use clear extension points (e.g., registering new routes, services, or handlers) rather than switches or long `if/elif` chains scattered across the codebase.
  - When adding new behavior, prefer composing existing services or utilities instead of editing their internals, unless you are fixing a bug or paying down clear technical debt.

- **ORM usage for complex queries**:
  - For simple CRUD and straightforward filters, an ORM or ODM is acceptable.
  - For highly complex or performance-critical queries and aggregations, prefer **direct MongoDB queries/aggregations** instead of forcing them through an ORM abstraction.
  - Keep complex query logic in repository modules with clear, well-named functions so they remain testable and reusable.
